rchitecture, the contributors consider both private and public/civic architecture. They showcase the architectural reflections of a Scotland finding its new elites by providing new research, analysing paradigms such as Holyrood and Hamilton Palace, as well as external reference points such as Paris tenements, Roman precedents and English parallels. Typologically, the book is broad in scope, covering the architecture and design of country estate and also the urban scene in the era before Edinburgh New Town.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aArchitecturezScotlandxHistoryy17th century. 0aArchitecturezScotlandxHistoryy18th century. 0aArchitecture, Scottish. 4aScottish Studies. 7aARCHITECTURE / Criticism.2bisacsh1 aBrown, Marilyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavey, Ali, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDingwall, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGodard Desmarest, Clarisse, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonzález-Longo, Cristina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGordon Brown, Iain, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuidicini, Giovanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaynes, Nick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHumm, Louisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJeffery, Sally, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLamb, Rory, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLegard, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 a